{"id": "0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1.pdf_order_f1ef17b2", "checked": "verified", "after": "Goodwin (1981) presents sample snippets of conversations recorded in the wild, annotated to show when the gaze of a listener turns to meet the gaze of the speaker", "url": "http://erichorvitz.com/sigdial2015_incremental_coordination.pdf", "type": "order", "before": "Goodwin (1981) highlights a variety of coordination mechanisms that speakers use to achieve mutual orientation at the beginning and throughout turns, such as pausing, adding phrasal breaks, lengthening spoken units, and even changing the structure of the sentence on the fly to secure the listener's attention.", "max_diffs": 2, "pdf": "multi_column_page1.pdf", "source": "multi_column/0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1_pg1.pdf"}
{"id": "0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1.pdf_order_617b0ab3", "checked": "verified", "after": "Following a brief review of related work, we describe the proposed approach in more detail in Section 3.", "url": "http://erichorvitz.com/sigdial2015_incremental_coordination.pdf", "type": "order", "before": "1 Introduction", "max_diffs": 2, "pdf": "multi_column_page1.pdf", "source": "multi_column/0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1_pg1.pdf"}
{"id": "0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1.pdf_order_9145bc9b", "checked": "verified", "after": "The model centers on computing whether the listener's attention matches a set of attentional demands for the utterance at hand.", "url": "http://erichorvitz.com/sigdial2015_incremental_coordination.pdf", "type": "order", "before": "(marked with an  underline). In the examples reproduced below from Goodwin's work, pauses and repeats are used to align grammatical sentences with a listener's gaze:", "max_diffs": 1, "pdf": "multi_column_page1.pdf", "source": "multi_column/0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1_pg1.pdf"}
{"id": "0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1.pdf_order_0c99e823", "checked": "verified", "after": "While most work to date in spoken dialog systems has focused on the acoustic channel in physically situated multimodal systems, an opportunity arises to use vision to take the participants' attention into account when coordinating on the production of system utterances.", "url": "http://erichorvitz.com/sigdial2015_incremental_coordination.pdf", "type": "order", "before": "Inspired by studies of human-human conversations, we present methods for incrementally coordinating speech production with listeners' visual foci of attention.", "max_diffs": 1, "pdf": "multi_column_page1.pdf", "source": "multi_column/0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1_pg1.pdf"}
{"id": "0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1.pdf_order_67e1c2bc", "checked": "verified", "after": "(process indicated by the broken  underline), as in the following:", "url": "http://erichorvitz.com/sigdial2015_incremental_coordination.pdf", "type": "order", "before": "Participants in a conversation coordinate with one another on producing turns, and often co-produce language by using verbal and non-verbal signals, including gaze, gestures, prosody and grammatical structures.", "max_diffs": 2, "pdf": "multi_column_page1.pdf", "source": "multi_column/0005784d0d255f6652180433936fa2998188_page_1_pg1.pdf"}
